article.headline: Golden Eagles set school record for points
article.linkText: Marquette's record night dooms short-handed S. Florida
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Marquette put together a complete game.

	   Dwyane Wade scored 21 points as Marquette (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today, No. 24 AP) beat
short-handed South Florida 96-63 on Saturday night.

	   The Golden Eagles (10-3, 2-1 Conference USA) led by as many as
37 points and set a school record for most points in a conference
game.

	   "It was a great team effort on the defensive end, which
continued to propel us throughout the game,'' Marquette coach Tom
Crean said.

	   The Bulls (7-6, 0-2) brought 10 healthy players but finished
with only five.

	   With 9:51 left in the first half, starting guard Marlyn Bryant
injured his right knee and did not return. Bryant was hurt during
Marquette's 17-0 run that gave the Golden Eagles a 30-8 lead.

Marquette led by as many as 28 points in the first half and limited
the Bulls' leading scorer, Will McDonald, to three free throws.

	   The Bulls were already playing without starting forward Jimmy
Baxter, benched for "behavior detrimental to the team,'' according
to a school spokesman.

	   But after freshman forward Yusuf Baker left in the second half
with a sprained ankle and Brandon Brigman and Danny Oglesby fouled
out, Bulls coach Seth Greenberg inserted Baxter with about 11
minutes to play. Moments later McDonald fouled out.

	   "I don't think our 2-2 zone would have been any good,''
Greenberg joked.

	   Terrence Leather, who led South Florida with 20 points, played
the last five minutes with four fouls.

	   Steve Novak scored 15 points for Marquette, while Scott Merritt
and Travis Diener each added 13. Diener also had 12 assists.

	  "I think when teams come in here, they know it's a tough place
to play,'' Diener said. "We respect that and play pretty hard.''
